#Notes

##Stacks

- LIFO, all operations at one end called **top** (initially set top = -1)

- underflow, overflow - exceptions

- **Implementations**

  1. Simple Array based implementation
  2. Dynamic array based implementation
  3. Linked list implementation

- **Simple Array based implementation**

  - **TC** for all operations is **O(1)**
  - **TC** for push operation is **O(1)** if the array size is in bounds. 
  - **SC** is **O(n)**
  - Limitation is that max size of the stack must be defined and cannot be changed.

- **Dynamic array based implementation**

  - This implementation is overcome the limitation of simple array based impl.

  - If the array size is out of bounds, create a new array double the array size.

  - for n = 2 create array size = 4

    for n = 16 create array of size 32.

    this is basically **equal to 2n**. 

  - Therefore, **for n push operations** we are **doubling the array** **logn** **times**.

  - **TC** for n push operations is **O(n)** 

    because, T(n) = 1+2+4+8+ --- +n

    T(n) = O(n)

  - **TC** for all other operations is **O(1)**

  - **SC** is **O(n)**

  - **Limitation** is that too many doublings can cause memory overflow exception

- **Linked list implementation**

  - Push operatation is done by inserting element at the head (top).
  - Pop operation by removing element from head (top).
  - **TC** for all operations **O(1)**
  - **TC** for delete stack is **O(n)**
  - **SC** for n push operations is **O(n)**

- The **amortized time** of a push operation is the average time taken by a push over the series of operations i.e **T(n)/n**

  - For **Incremental**: O(n^2)/n = **O(n)**
  - For **Doubling**: O(n)/n = **O(1)**

##Queues

- FIFO
- Two pointers used:
  -  **front**: start element, deletions at front
  - **rear**: last element, Insertions at rear
- Enqueue (add), Dequeue (remove)
- Overflow, Underflow
- Operations: enqueue, dequeue, peek, isEmpty, size
- **Implementations**
  1. Simple Circular Array based implementation
  2. Dynamic Circular Array based implementation
  3. Linked list implementation 
- **Simple Circular Array based implementation**
  - Insertions are performed at the end and deletions at the front
  - So, the initial slots of the array would be empty and gets wasted. This is not efficient. 
  - **So use a circular array** where the last element and the first array elements are contiguous.
  - With this circular array, if there are any free slots at the beginning, the rear pointer can go to the next free slot. 
  - **TC** for all operations is O(1)
  - **SC** for n add operations is O(n)
  - **Limitation** is that size is fixed
- **Dynamic Circular Array based implementation**
  - **TC** is **O(1)**
  - **SC** is **O(n)**
- **Linked list implementation**
  - **TC** is **O(1)**
  - **SC** is **O(n)**

##Heaps

* It is a tree with some special properties

* Basic requirements 

  1. Value of a node must be `>=` or `<=` the values of its children.

     This is also called as **heap property**

  2. All leaves should be at h or h-1 (complete binary tree)

  3. Heap should form a complete Btree

  A Heap uses *Complete Binary Trees* to avoid holes in the array. See the figure below to see the difference between that and an Incomplete Binary Tree:

  ```
  Complete BTree    
      11
     /   \
    5     2
   / \   / 
  6  17 14 
  
  Incomplete BTree
      11
     /   \
    5     2
     \   / 
     17 14 
  ```



  Below mentioned heap is an invalid heap, because 

  (11 > 5,2) (5 < 6,17) (2 < 14,13) All parent nodes must have the same property (> or <)

  ```
      11
     /   \
    5     2
   / \   / \
  6  17 14 13
  ```

* Elements of a Heap are not sorted. Largest ior smallest element is always placed at the top depending on what kind of heap we are using.

* Types of Heaps

  1. **Min heap**: value of a node should be <= to values of its children

  2. **Max heap**: value of a node should be >= to values of its children

  3. **Binary heap**: 

     * In practice Binary heaps are enough and we concentrate on binary min and binary max heaps.

     * Each node can have up to 2 children

     * It is implemented using arrays (unlike BTs where BTs are implemented using stack)

     * Heaps are complete binary trees, so there wont be any wastage of memory locations

     * Can perform `insert()`, `delete()`, `extractmax()`, and `decreaseKey()` operations in O(logn) time

     * Variations of Binary heaps: 

       1. Binomial heap
       2. Fibonacci heap

       These variations can perform `union()` in O(logn) time where as Binary heap takes O(n)

* **Why heaps are implemented using arrays and not trees? [like BTree using stacks]**

  1. Lower memory usage(no need to store 3 pointer)
  2. Easier memory management i.e just one object is allocated instead of n
  3. Better locality of reference (Items in heap are relatively closer together in memory)
  4. Using arrarys is a good choice if we know that data is constant
  5. If the heap size grows deeper, then this array has to be copied to a larger array and this is time expensive.

* **Finding the parent of a node**

  * For a node at `ith` location, its parent is at `(i-1)/2` location

    i.e Node at i = parent at ((i-1)/2) location.

    ```
        17
       /   \
     13     6
     / \   / \
    1   4 2   5
    ```

    In the above example, if we consider node 6, it is at i=2, therefore its parent would be at (2-1)/2 = 1/2 = 0 i.e 0th location, which is node 17.

    **important**: All of the parent nodes are present in the first half of the array with the last parent at n/2th position(in this case at 2nd index) 

    **Above heap placement in array**

    | 0    | 1    | 2    | 3    | 4    | 5    | 6    |
    | ---- | ---- | ---- | ---- | ---- | ---- | ---- |
    | 17   | 13   | 6    | 1    | 4    | 2    | 5    |

* **Finding children of a node**

  * For a parent node at `ith` location,
    * **Left child** will be at **(2i+1)** location
    * **Right child** will be at **(2i+2)** location

* Main operations on a heap

  1. **getMin()/getMax()**
  2. **extractMin()/extractMax()**
  3. **insert()/delete()**

* **Max element** in max heap is always at root, i.e at arry[0]

* **Heapifying an element**

  The process of adjusting the  location of the inserted element in to heap and make it a heap again is called **heapifying**

  * In a max heap, to heapify an element,
    * find the maximum of its children and swap it with current element
    * continue until heap property is satisfied at every node in the heap
    * In heapifying process, 
      1. **Percolate down**: The process of moving from top to bottom 
      2. **Percolate up**: The process of moving from bottom to up
  * **TC** of heapifying is **O(logn)**
  * **SC** is **O(1)**
  * If we are dealing with a n number of input elements to be inserted and heapified, it takes **O(nlogn)** time in total, because each insert takes **O(logn)** time and n elements take **O(nlogn)**
  * *In a complete BTree of n nodes, there are n/2 leaf nodes and the leaf nodes always satisfies the heap property and no need to heapify them.*
  * *We just have to heapify the remaining n/2 non leaf nodes.* 

* **Deleting an element from a heap**

  * In a standard heap, deleting a max element is only allowed
  * So, deleting an element from a heap is just deleting the first element (root) from the heap
  * copy the root in to some variable
  * Then, copy the last element in to the root
  * Then **percolate down**
  * **TC** is **O(logn)**
  * **SC** is **O(1)**

* **Search for an element in a heap** 

  * **TC** is O(n), because we have to go through all the elements and the heapify func doesn't help with this operation.

* **Inserting an element in to a heap**

  * Increase the heap size
  * Keep new element at the end of the heap
  * Then **perolate up**
  * **TC** is **O(logn)**

  **MaxHeap Implementation**

  Refer <https://github.com/namratha-prabhu/DSA/blob/master/src/main/java/Heaps/MaxHeap.java>

  **MinHeap Implementation**

  Refer <https://github.com/namratha-prabhu/DSA/blob/master/src/main/java/Heaps/MinHeap.java>

* Deleting an element uses percolate down and inserting uses percolate up.

* **Where are heaps used?**

  1. **Order statistics**: For efficiently finding the smallest or largest element in an array.

  2. **Priority Queues**: PQ's can be efficiently implemented using Binary heap because it supports insert, delete, extractMax, decreaseKey operations in O(logn) time.

     We can use Binomoial Heaps and Fibonacci Heaps to perform union() in O(logn) time, where as Binary heap takes O(n) time.

  3. Heap implemented PQ's are used in Graph algos like **Prim's algo and Dijkstra's algo**. 

  4. **Sorting**: **HeapSort** is especially useful for sorting `arrays` because Heaps, unlike almost all other types of trees - are usually implemented in arrays, not as linked data structures!

## Priority Queues

* PQ is an extension of queue with following properties

  * Every item has a priority associated with it
  * An element with high priority is dequeued before an element with low priority i.e the order in which the elements enter the queue may not be the same in which they are processed.
  * if two elements have the same priority, they are served according to their order in the queue
  * In java PQ has a default initial capacity of 11, which can be overridden using **initialCapacity** parameter in appropriate constructor.
  * PriorityQueue is **not thread safe**. Use `PriorityBlockingQueue` in concurrent environment.
  * PQ in java is self-order queue by elements' natural order, smallest at head, largest at rear. When we poll the queue, it returns the head object from the queue.
  * Objects added to PriorityQueue MUST be comparable.
  * It provides **O(log(n))** time for add and poll methods.

* PQ supports the following operations

  * **insert(item, priority)**
  * **getMin()/getMax()** (also equivalent to **getHighestPriority**)
  * **deleteMin()/deleteMax()** (also equivalent to **deleteHighestPriority()**)
  * **Kth-smallest/kth largest()**
  * **Size**
  * **Heap sort**: sort elements in the PQ based on priority(key)

* **Applications**:

  1. **Job scheduling**: which is prioritized instead of serving in first come first serve
  2. **Data Compression**: Huffman coding algorithm
  3. **Shortest Path algos**: Dijkstra's algorithm
  4. **Minimum spanning tree algos**: Prim's algo
  5. **Event driven simulation**
  6. **Selection problem**: Finding Kth smallest or largest element.

* Types of PQ

  1. **Ascending PQ**: if the item with the smallest key has the highest priority (i.e delete smallest element always because smallest element has highest priority)
  2. **Descending PQ**: if the item with the largest key has the highest priority (i.e delete largest element always because largest element has highest priority)

* **Implementations**

  | Implementation                                               | Insertion               | Deletion |
  | ------------------------------------------------------------ | ----------------------- | -------- |
  | Unordered Array Impl                                         | O(1)                    | O(n)     |
  | Unordered list Impl                                          | O(1)                    | O(n)     |
  | ordered Array Impl                                           | O(n) because of sorting | O(1)     |
  | ordered list Impl                                            | O(n) because of sorting | O(1)     |
  | Binary Search Trees Impl                                     | O(logn)                 | O(logn)  |
  | Balances BST impl                                            | O(logn)                 | O(logn)  |
  | Binary Heap impl<br /> (Search takes O(logn), <br />finding max/min takes O(1)) | O(logn)                 | O(logn)  |

## Graphs

* A graph is a set of **vertices** (nodes) that are connected to each other via **edges** in the form of a network.

* These are ds used for finding solutions for problems like what is the faster route between places.

* Graph is a pair(V, E) where

  * V = set of nodes called **vertices**
  * E = collection of pairs vertices, called **edges**

* **Directed Edge**

  * Ordered pair of vertices, it means it has direction
  * U ———> V, here U is the origin and V is the destination

* **Undirected edge**

  * Unordered pair of vertices, it means no direction
  * U ——— V

* **Directed graph**

* **Undirected Graph**

* When an edge connects two vertices, the vertoces are said to be adjacent to each other and the edge is incident on both vertices.

* A graph with no cycles is called **Tree**. A tree is an **acyclic connected graph**.

* A self loop is an edge that connects a vertex to itself

* Two edges are parallel if they connect the same pair of vertices.

* The **Degree** of a vertex is the number of edges incident on it.

* There are two types of degrees:

  - **In-Degree of Vertex**: Total Number of incoming edges connected to a vertex.
  - **Out-Degree of Vertex**: Total Number of outgoing edges connected to a vertex.

* A **subgraph** is a subset of a graph's edges (with associated vertices) that form a graph

* A **path** in a graph is a sequence of adjacent vertices.

* A **simple path** is a path with no repeated vertices

* A **cycle** is a path where the first and last vertices are the same 

* A **simple cycle** is a cycle with no repeated vertices and edges

* A **graph is connected** if there is a path from every vertex to every other vertex

* A **directed acyclic graph [DAG]** is a connected grapth with no cycles

* A **forest** is a disjoint set of trees

* A ***spanning tree*** of a connected graph is a subgraph that contains all of that graphs vertices and is a single tree.

* A **Spanning forest** of a graph is the union of spanning trees of its connected components

* **Bipartite Graph**: 

* **Weighted graphs** are graphs with integers(weights) assigned to each edge to represent distances or costs

* A graph with all edges is called a **Complete graph**

* Graphs witn relatively few edges are called **Sparse Graphs** (edges < |v|log|v|)  

* Grapsh with relatively few of the possible edges missing are called **dense graphs**

* **Directed weighted graphs** are called **network**

* Number of Edges in an undirected graph, **E = 0 to |V|(|V|-1)/2**, because each vertex can connect to every other vertex. Check notes for proof. This is for undirected graph

  - where |V| is the number of vertices
  - where |E| is the number of edges

* Max number of edges in a directed graph iof V vertices, **E = V(V-1)**, because the edges can go in both directions.

* If the edges are allowed to go from a vertex to the same vertex, then the Max number of edges in a directed graph iof V vertices, **E= V^2**

* **Graph Representation**

  1. **Adjacency Matrix**

     - we use a matrix of size V x V
     - All values of the matrix are boolean
     - Let the matrix be adj. 
     - The value of adj[U, V] is 1, if there is an edge from U to V and 0 otherwise.
     - In case of **Undirected Graphs**,
       - each **edge** is represented by **2 bits**
       - matrix is **always symmetric** (Symmetric matrix - if the transpose is equal to the matrix itself), i.e edge from U to V and V to U are represented by 1
       - Max number of edges **E = V(V-1)/2**
     - In case of **Directed Graphs**,
       - Both U to V and V to U are different since they are directed.
       - Max number of edges **E = V(V-1)** 
       - **Main Operations:** 
         1. addEdge(int i, int j)
         2. removeEdge(int i, int j)
         3. isEdge(int i, int j)
       - Adj maxtrix representation is **good** if the **graph is dense**.
       - Adj maxtrix representation is **bad** if the graph is **sparse** because then most of the matrix cells remain unused which leads to waste of memory.
       - [Implementation](<https://github.com/namratha-prabhu-interview-prep/DSA/blob/master/src/main/java/Graphs/AdjacencyMatrix.java>)
       - **TC** for both **directed graph** and  **undirected graph** is **O(n^2)**, because we have to go through n nodes twice to add edge U to V and V to U
       - **SC** is **O(n^2)**, because it needs a matrix of size n x n, n is thenumber of vertices.

  2. **Adjacency List **

     - In this, all the vertices connected to a vertex V are listed on an adj list for that vertex V.

     - For each vertex V, we use a LL and the list of nodes represnts the connections between V and other vertices to which V has an edge

     - **The total number of LL = Number of vertices in the graph**

     - For this, the order of edges in the input is important because they determine the order of the vertices on the adjacency list.

     - The edges are processed based on the order in which they appear on the adj list.

     - **Disadvantages**:

       1. Deleting a node from the adj list is very inefficient because to delete a node we need to search other vertices's LL, as it might have an edge with other nodes.

          The above problem can be solved by linking the 2 list nodes that correspond to a particular edge and making the adjacency list doubly linked.

          But these take extra links and are risky to process.

     - [Implementation](<https://github.com/namratha-prabhu-interview-prep/DSA/blob/master/src/main/java/Graphs/AdjacencyList.java>)

     - **TC**

       - for **undirected graph**, it is **O(|V| + |E|)**, 
         - because we would loop through the array of lists to create V vertices, which takes O(1) for 1 vertex and for V vertices it would take **O(|v|)**.
         - and then we would add edges to the vertices's list. The number of edges incident on a vertex is called that vertices's **degree**. So for each vertex it would take **deg(v)** time. 
         - Therefore in total it would take **O(V) + deg(V1) + deg(V2) + ---**, which is nothing but **O(|V| +|E|)**.

       - For **directed graph**, it is **O(V + V^2)** which is nothing but **O(V^2)**, because 
         - because we would loop through the array of lists to create V vertices, which takes O(1) for 1 vertex and for V vertices it would take **O(|v|)**.
         - In a directed graph, in the worst case the **maximum number of edges** in a graph is **O(V^2)**. 
         - Therefore it is **O(V + V^2)** [can also be O(V + E), because E = V^2] which is equal is **O(V^2)**.

     - **SC**

       * Space required is **O(E)**, where O(E) might be equal to **O(V X V)** if the graph is a directed connected graph. In this case SC is too high. But for every other case the value of E would be less.

* | **Operation**                       | **Adjacency List** | **Adjacency Matrix** |
  | ----------------------------------- | ------------------ | -------------------- |
  | **For alll V vertices and E edges** | O(V + E)           | O(V^2)               |
  | **Add Edge**                        | O(1)               | O(1)                 |
  | **Remove Edge**                     | O(E)               | O(1)                 |
  | **Search**                          | O(V)               | O(1)                 |

* **Comparison between Adj matric and list**

  1. If your model frequently manipulates vertices, the adjacency list is a better choice
  2. If you are dealing primarily with edges, the adjacency matrix is the more efficient approach.

* **Bipartite Graph**

  * **A Bipartite Graph** is a special kind of Graph, in which the vertices can be divided into two disjoint sets *U* and *V* such that no vertex of *U* is adjacent to any other vertex in *U* and no vertex of *V* is adjacent to any other vertex in *V*. Vertices in *U* have edges that connect it to vertices in *V*.

    2. Green colored vertices belong to a disjoint set *V*.

  * **Types of Bipartite graph**

    1. **Complete Bipartite Graphs**: It connects each vertex from disjoint set U to each vertex from disjoint set V.

    2. **Star Graphs**: It is a complete Bipartite graph if a single vertex belongs to one set and all the remaining vertices belong to the other set.

    3. **Acyclic Graphs**: A graph with no cycles.

* **Graph Traversal Algorithms** [Graph search]

  1. **Depth First Search**: 

     - It is similar to pre order traversal (DLR) of trees, so **uses stack**
     - **Back edge**: edge that leads to an already discovered vertex is called as a Back edge and the other edges are called **tree edges**
     - Deleting back edges from the graph generates a tree and hence the other edges are called tree edges.
     - The final generated tree is called as **DFS tree**
     - **Forward edge**: From ancestor to descendent
     - **cross edge**: between a tree or subtree
     - Two criterias for DFS impl, 
       1. vertex is **unvisited**, then use **false**
       2. vertex is **visited**, then use **true**
     - Initially all the vertices are marked unvisited (false)
     - DFS starts from the root node and visits connecting vertices
     - if the edge leads to a visited vertex, then backtrack to the current vertex.
     - If the edge leads to an unvisited vertex, then go to that vertex and start processing from that vertex [new vertex becomes current vertex]
     - Follow this process until we reach the dead end [at this pont start backtracking]
     - The process terminates when the backtracking leads to the start vertex.
     - Implementation
     - The order in which the vertices are processed is called **DFS numbers** of the vertices.
     - DFS algo works even if the given graph has connected components
     - **Implementation**
       1. [DFS using adj list](<https://github.com/namratha-prabhu-interview-prep/DSA/blob/master/src/main/java/Graphs/DFSUsingAdjList.java>)
       2. [DFS using adj matrix](<https://github.com/namratha-prabhu-interview-prep/DSA/blob/master/src/main/java/Graphs/DFSUsingAdjMatrix.java>)
     - **TC** 
       - using **Adj List** for representing the graph, **O(V + E)**
       - using **Adj Matrix**, **O(V^2)**
     - **Applications**: Topological sorting

  2. **Breadth First Search**

     - Similar to level order traversal in trees, hence BFS also **uses Queues**
     - BFS starts at level 0, then in 1st stage it visits all vertices at level 1
     - Then in second stage, it visits all vertices in level 2.
     - BFS continues this process until all the levels of a graph are completed.
     - Queue is used to store the vertices at a level
     - Initially all vertices are marked false.
     - **Implementation**
       1. [BFS using adj list](<https://github.com/namratha-prabhu-interview-prep/DSA/blob/master/src/main/java/Graphs/BFSUsingAdjList.java>)
       2. [BFS uisng adj matrix](<https://github.com/namratha-prabhu-interview-prep/DSA/blob/master/src/main/java/Graphs/BFSUsingAdjMatrix.java>)
     - **TC** 
       - Using adj lists, **O(V + E)**
       - Using adj matrix, **O(V^2)**
     - **Applications**
       1. Finding the shortest path between two nodes
       2. testing a graph for its bipartiteness.

  3. **Comparison between DFS and BFS**

     | **DFS**                                                      | **BFS**                                 |
     | ------------------------------------------------------------ | --------------------------------------- |
     | Uses min memory<br />because no need to saving pointers to <br />children at each level | More memory                             |
     | If we are looking for something at the <br />**bottom of the tree**, then DFS gives the **shortest path** | Takes a long times and **longest path** |
     | If we are looking for something at the **top of the tree**, then DFS gives the **longest path** and takes a lot of time | Gives the **shortest path**             |
